spanGrp.span: Recorded by Maïa Ponsonnet on 12th July 2012 in the afternoon, at Maggie's house in Weemol, on the veranda, working on Dalabon with Maggie Tukumba. She comments on photos series G6. Transcribed and translated by Ellison Luk 2017 (under MP's supervision).
ka-h-medmo-yer-mu kardu ngey nga-h-medmo-dabk-a ka-h-mon? (MP orientates the story towards shame and protection from shame.)
She's ashamed...and maybe me, I'm blocking her face, is that right?

u.seg: I wonder it is 'you shut her gaze' = 'block her from seeing' but it is not possible to tell.
It is he > her, not they (bukah is for sg A). 'h' is sufficient for 'high', saves space - ney = n-ey
He looks at her this way (A is sg)

spanGrp.span: MT20120713b_001 bah yu no na yu bin shadimap im

u.seg: or block her from viewing? probably both = protect from sight

spanGrp.span: MT20120713b_001 yu bin shadimap ay langa im wei
maybe because he's looking at her this way.
He looks at her this way,

u.seg: medmo-yer-mu = ashamed from being exposed to the view of others - I'm not sure about 'turned', maybe 'from that way'
she is turning her face to herself ?

spanGrp.span: but you block (the view of) her face.
MT20120713b_001 yu bin shadimap im ay
Or maybe because I'm blocking the side (of her face)
She is ashamed, (turned) that way, but
she on the other hand, her face is turned away.
MT20120713b_001 wan said imin labta luk
You block (the view of) her face,
she is looking over here, and
he is looking at her this way.
But you are sitting in the middle (between them),
So you block the view of her face.
MT20120713b_001 yu bin shadimap im ay
She looks that way over there,
MT20120713b_001 im luk darrei na said wei
Maybe even here I'm blocking her
new entry / sub entry MT20120713b_001 dumadji yu bin langa front blanga im - rait pleis na yu bin sidan bla im
and she's blocking her own gaze a bit as well,
because you keep looking at her.
You keep insistently looking at her.

u.seg: and what are these two doing, to her...

spanGrp.span: he keeps looking at your backs together.

u.seg: This is what this one is doing.
gestures swing between Maïa and one of the men; yihda='two'?

spanGrp.span: And what are these two thinking, she...
MT20120713b_001 wod im doin dijan gel

u.seg: he's spying on you - 'without you knowing/realizing' rather than 'secretly' perhaps, but it's fine.

spanGrp.span: she has her back against them here.
MT20120713b_001 dis gel im langa midul olataim
This is what this one is doing.

u.seg: I think these two annotations translate as 'maybe she's jealous trying to keep her for herself, he thinks this on the man'. It's hard to know who does what, and the pointing only partly helps. And no ERG!
mistranscription on my behalf: it's ka-h-yin
gestures between Maïa and one of the men

spanGrp.span: He keeps spying on the two of you.
MT20120713b_001 im lukluk langa mibala jinikin weya sneaky way
MT20120713b_001 kah-dorrudh-djurrudjurru-namrrun - matbi dijan lubra im jilis la dat notha lubra langos im blokim im bla luk mi
*bunu nga-h-ngabb-un dolku-ngan not repeated dolku-ngabbu-n repeated instead firmly
I have my back turned on them two
You have your back on them two.
You have your back on them two.
And even here I have my back against them.
yu bin gibit bekbun la dubala
You give your back to these two.
Kriol Kriol Kriol Kriol Kriol Kriol

u.seg: -wali is 'in turn' rather than 'in return'? - 'then' to reflect SEQ?

spanGrp.span: You have your back on her, and she has her back on you in return

u.seg: lardehmu = from Kriol ledim from English let him - malk can be glossed as 'country', and malk-nan means 'look around' = 'you're not letting her look around'

spanGrp.span: MT20120713b_001 ola taim yu blokim im ay im kan lukaraun matbi im trai lukinat det men - dadsde wei im nogudbinji
You're not letting her look around this way

u.seg: dorrung is probably 'body', nam is 'wear', but I'm not sure how this compound works
gestures to Maïa and the girl

spanGrp.span: She can't look around (at the man),
but you can all the time.
MT20120713b_001 yu olwes blokim blanga luk langa boys
nidjarra mahkih kardu kardu ngah-medmo dabk-a
Here as well maybe I'm blocking her face.
This is why her head is bent down.

u.seg: here FOC translates as 'keep' : you just blck her face > you only block of face > blocking her face is all you do > you keep blciking her face
And her she's not looking around nothing. (implied: she cannot do it - because you prevent her)

spanGrp.span: I'm sitting facing the two of them
MT20120713b_001 yu kip blokimbad im im kan ges thru blanga luk ka dubala men
She cannot look around at the men (the way that you are)
Nuh-uh. You have your side to the two of them.
No, you have your side to the two men.
